hands_on_practices.solution:
1. For BCC, the nearest-neighbor distance is along the body diagonal. The atoms touch, so the length of the body diagonal is $4r$. In terms of the lattice constant $a_{BCC}$, this is $\sqrt{3}a_{BCC} = 4r$.
$$a_{BCC}=\frac{4r}{\sqrt{3}}.$$
The BCC conventional cell contains 2 atoms, so the volume per atom is:
$$V_{BCC}=\frac{a_{BCC}^3}{2}
=\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{4r}{\sqrt{3}}\right)^3
=\frac{1}{2} \frac{64r^3}{3\sqrt{3}} = \frac{32r^3}{3\sqrt{3}}.$$

2. For FCC, the nearest-neighbor distance lies along the face diagonal. The length of the face diagonal is $4r$, which is equal to $\sqrt{2}a_{FCC}$.
$$a_{FCC}=\frac{4r}{\sqrt{2}} = 2\sqrt{2}r.$$
The FCC conventional cell contains 4 atoms, so the volume per atom is:
$$V_{FCC}=\frac{a_{FCC}^3}{4}
=\frac{(2\sqrt{2}r)^3}{4}
=\frac{16\sqrt{2}r^3}{4} = 4\sqrt{2}r^3.$$

3. The fractional change is calculated as $\frac{V_{FCC} - V_{BCC}}{V_{FCC}}$:
$$\frac{\Delta V}{V_{FCC}}
=1-\frac{V_{BCC}}{V_{FCC}}
=1 - \frac{32r^3 / (3\sqrt{3})}{4\sqrt{2}r^3}
=1 - \frac{32}{12\sqrt{6}}
=1 - \frac{8}{3\sqrt{6}}
=1 - \frac{8\sqrt{6}}{18}
=1 - \frac{4\sqrt{6}}{9}
= \frac{9-4\sqrt{6}}{9}.$$
